    text: "As far as negotiation versus litigation, I think it's always good to have. Multiple people involved when it come. And when I say people, um, not just the client, but people within the firm as well. Because for me, I don't really like to negotiate. For me, my brain goes from, okay, I am asking X dollars, and you have low balled me when I say low ball, or you, I'm talking about the insurance companies. And the moment the insurance company's low ball, and I feel like the gap is too wide. And when I say too wide, I am talking about, let's say if we were to litigate it, our fees do go up to 40%. So I have to take that into consideration. If it's, if we're only, let's say a couple thousand dollars apart, then it's probably not worth litigating and having our fees go up 40% and incurring, let's say $500 just to file the lawsuit, another couple hundred hundred dollars to hire a private investigator, go serve the lawsuit, and then go through the whole litigation process for many months after that, for the client to go and sit through a deposition that could be anywhere between four to seven hours long, no need to cook them through all that over a couple thousand dollars. It has to be worth it. But of course. That's also based off of the client communication. Some people, they're, they don't care about what they walk away with. They're trying to teach them a lesson and they're trying to teach. When I say them, the insurance companies, they feel hurt. And that's typically when clients actually come. I hear it all the time. They always start off with, I actually never wanted to hire an attorney. I wasn't even thinking about hiring an attorney, but the insurance company isn't listening to me. That's always what it comes down to. It's the insurance company not listening when they throw a settlement offer out there, and the client is but what about my treatment? But what about my pain? But what about this imaging I need? And they're like, no, yeah. Here's a hundred dollars more. But it doesn't answer the question. Just throwing money out there doesn't answer the questions and address their concerns. And so that kind of conversation needs to be had with the client. Some clients are like, I want to have the fees go up to 40% and even if it means I walk away with nothing at the end of it all, I want this to be litigated and I get full value. But some people, if they have let's say anxiety, and I know just based off of my relationship with them that I've built during the case, I see that they're probably gonna have some troubles with things like depositions. And when I say depositions, these are. Sometimes in person after COVID, most of it's on Zoom, but these are recorded interviews that the other side's attorney does, and they will sit there and drill you for anywhere between four to seven hours asking you all these million questions. And people get nervous, people don't wanna go through that. And people get panic attacks. And I can gauge it based off of just the relationship we have. , At this point I can see, okay, they're gonna be able to do it or they're not gonna be able to do it. And if that's the case, regardless of what I think the case is worth and what I think we should do to get the proper compensation, ultimately that can hurt the client's mental and emotional health and wellbeing. And so I think that's a big no-no. So there's been a situation where, let's say. We had a offer, I think it was around like 50 grand, but in my head I said, okay, this case is worth a hundred grand. So I talked to a client and I talked to them about, going through litigation and what that entailed and what that meant for them. And they said, absolutely not. I don't feel comfortable suing the person or I don't feel comfortable going through litigation. I don't remember exactly what it was, but she was very against the idea. And I said, okay, if that is the case, we are not getting what I think you deserve what I think you fully deserve. We will not be, we will be leaving money on the table. And she was okay with that. So ultimately, I think it's, as long as the client is well informed and they know what it means to choose path A versus path B versus path C and what that means and the end result, if they are happy with their choices and I know that they made that decision, then I'm happy to, and of course we will still get the most we can within that given circumstance. So whatever is available, we will scrape off as much as we can without adding the burden onto the clients.",
